  "mermaid": "graph TD\n    %% Target Protein and Signals\n    A[Target Protein Synthesis] --> B[Protein in Cytoplasm]\n    C[Damage Signal] --> D[Misfolded Protein]\n    E[Cell Cycle Signal] --> F[/Cyclin Degradation Signal/]\n    G[Stress Signal] --> H[Stress Response Protein]\n    \n    B --> I{Protein Fate<br/>Decision?}\n    D --> I\n    F --> I\n    H --> I\n    \n    %% Degron Recognition\n    I -->|Degradation| J{Degron<br/>Present?}\n    J -->|Yes| K[Degron Exposed]\n    K --> L[E3 Ligase Recognition]\n    \n    %% E3 Ligase Types\n    L --> M{Which E3<br/>Ligase?}\n    M -->|SCF| N[SCF Complex Skp1-Cdc53-F-box]\n    M -->|APC/C| O[APC/C Complex]\n    M -->|HECT| P[HECT Domain E3]\n    M -->|RING| Q[RING Domain E3]\n    \n    %% Ubiquitin Activation\n    R[Free Ubiquitin] --> S[E1 Uba1 Enzyme]\n    S --> T[ATP-Dependent Activation]\n    T --> U[Ubiquitin-E1 Thioester]\n    \n    %% Ubiquitin Conjugation\n    U --> V[E2 Ubc Enzyme]\n    V --> W[Ubiquitin Transfer to E2]\n    W --> X[Ubiquitin-E2 Thioester]\n    \n    %% E3-Mediated Ubiquitination\n    N --> Y[Substrate-SCF Binding]\n    O --> Y\n    P --> Y\n    Q --> Y\n    \n    X --> Y\n    Y --> ANDGATE1{E2-Ub AND E3-Substrate<br/>AND Lysine Available?}\n    \n    ANDGATE1 -->|Yes| Z[Ubiquitin Transfer to Substrate]\n    Z --> AA[Monoubiquitinated Protein]\n    \n    %% Polyubiquitin Chain Formation\n    AA --> AB{Continue<br/>Ubiquitination?}\n    AB -->|Yes| AC[K48-Linked Chain Extension]\n    AC --> AD[Polyubiquitin Chain]\n    AD --> AE{Chain Length<br/>\u2265 4 Ubiquitins?}\n    \n    AE -->|Yes| AF[/K48-Ub4+ Degradation Signal/]\n    AE -->|No| AB\n    \n    %% 26S Proteasome Recognition\n    AF --> AG[19S Regulatory Particle Recognition]\n    AG --> AH[Rpn10 Rpn13 Ubiquitin Receptors]\n    AH --> AI{Substrate<br/>Committed?}\n    \n    AI --> ANDGATE2{Polyubiquitinated AND<br/>19S Bound?}\n    ANDGATE2 -->|Yes| AJ[Substrate Engagement]\n    \n    %% Deubiquitination and Unfolding\n    AJ --> AK[Rpn11 Deubiquitinase]\n    AK --> AL[Ubiquitin Chain Removal]\n    AL --> AM[Ubiquitin Recycling]\n    AL --> AN[Substrate Unfolding]\n    \n    AN --> AO[AAA+ ATPase Ring]\n    AO --> AP[ATP-Dependent Unfolding]\n    AP --> AQ{Protein<br/>Unfolded?}\n    \n    AQ --> ANDGATE3{Unfolded AND<br/>20S Gate Open?}\n    ANDGATE3 -->|Yes| AR[Translocation into 20S]\n    \n    %% Proteolysis\n    AR --> AS[20S Catalytic Core]\n    AS --> AT[Threonine Protease Activity]\n    AT --> AU[Processive Proteolysis]\n    AU --> AV[Peptide Products]\n    AV --> AW[7-9 Amino Acid Peptides]\n    \n    %% Final Products\n    AW --> AX[Peptide Release]\n    AX --> AY[Cytoplasmic Peptidases]\n    AY --> AZ[Free Amino Acids]\n    \n    AM --> BA[Ubiquitin Pool Replenishment]\n    AZ --> BB[Amino Acid Pool]\n    BB --> BC[Protein Synthesis or Metabolism]\n    \n    %% Alternative Fates\n    I -->|Stable| BD[Functional Protein]\n    J -->|No| BE[/Protein Escapes Degradation/]\n    AI -->|No| BF[Substrate Release]\n    AQ -->|No| BG[/Failed Degradation/]\n    \n    %% Styling - GLMP Color Scheme\n    %% Red: Triggers & Inputs\n    \n    %% Yellow: Structures & Objects\n    \n    %% Green: Processing & Operations\n    \n    %% Blue: Intermediates & States\n    \n    %% Orange: OR Logic Gates\n    \n    %% Lavender: AND Logic Gates\n    \n    %% Violet: Products & Outputs\n\n    %% Semantic Color Styling\n\n    %% Semantic Color Styling\n\n    %% Semantic Color Styling\n\n    %% Semantic Color Styling\n    style A fill:#ffa726,color:#fff\n    style B fill:#51cf66,color:#fff\n    style C fill:#51cf66,color:#fff\n    style D fill:#51cf66,color:#fff\n    style E fill:#51cf66,color:#fff\n    style F fill:#e74c3c,color:#fff\n    style G fill:#51cf66,color:#fff\n    style H fill:#51cf66,color:#fff\n    style I fill:#7950f2,color:#fff\n    style J fill:#7950f2,color:#fff\n    style K fill:#b3e5fc,color:#000\n    style L fill:#42a5f5,color:#fff\n    style M fill:#7950f2,color:#fff\n    style N fill:#b3e5fc,color:#000\n    style O fill:#b3e5fc,color:#000\n    style P fill:#b3e5fc,color:#000\n    style Q fill:#b3e5fc,color:#000\n    style R fill:#b3e5fc,color:#000\n    style S fill:#ffa726,color:#fff\n    style T fill:#42a5f5,color:#fff\n    style U fill:#b3e5fc,color:#000\n    style V fill:#ffa726,color:#fff\n    style W fill:#b3e5fc,color:#000\n    style X fill:#b3e5fc,color:#000\n    style Y fill:#42a5f5,color:#fff\n    style ANDGATE1 fill:#7950f2,color:#fff\n    style Z fill:#b3e5fc,color:#000\n    style AA fill:#ffa726,color:#fff\n    style AB fill:#7950f2,color:#fff\n    style AC fill:#b3e5fc,color:#000\n    style AD fill:#b3e5fc,color:#000\n    style AE fill:#7950f2,color:#fff\n    style AF fill:#e74c3c,color:#fff\n    style AG fill:#b3e5fc,color:#000\n    style AH fill:#b3e5fc,color:#000\n    style AI fill:#7950f2,color:#fff\n    style ANDGATE2 fill:#7950f2,color:#fff\n    style AJ fill:#b3e5fc,color:#000\n    style AK fill:#b3e5fc,color:#000\n    style AL fill:#b3e5fc,color:#000\n    style AM fill:#b3e5fc,color:#000\n    style AN fill:#b3e5fc,color:#000\n    style AO fill:#b3e5fc,color:#000\n    style AP fill:#b3e5fc,color:#000\n    style AQ fill:#7950f2,color:#fff\n    style ANDGATE3 fill:#7950f2,color:#fff\n    style AR fill:#b3e5fc,color:#000\n    style AS fill:#b3e5fc,color:#000\n    style AT fill:#42a5f5,color:#fff\n    style AU fill:#b3e5fc,color:#000\n    style AV fill:#000000,color:#fff\n    style AW fill:#b3e5fc,color:#000\n    style AX fill:#b3e5fc,color:#000\n    style AY fill:#b3e5fc,color:#000\n    style AZ fill:#b3e5fc,color:#000\n    style BA fill:#b3e5fc,color:#000\n    style BB fill:#b3e5fc,color:#000\n    style BC fill:#ffa726,color:#fff\n    style BD fill:#ffa726,color:#fff\n    style BE fill:#e74c3c,color:#fff\n    style BF fill:#b3e5fc,color:#000\n    style BG fill:#e74c3c,color:#fff",
  "name": "Ubiquitin-Proteasome System and Protein Degradation",
  "notGates": 4,
  "notes": "This flowchart represents the complete ubiquitin-proteasome pathway with 58 nodes showing substrate recognition, ubiquitination cascade, proteasomal degradation, and product recycling. Contains 7 OR logic gates (protein fate decision, degron detection, E3 ligase selection, chain length check, substrate commitment, unfolding success, alternative fates) and 3 AND logic gates (ubiquitin transfer requires E2-Ub AND E3-substrate AND lysine; proteasome recognition requires polyubiquitination AND 19S binding; proteolysis requires unfolding AND 20S gate opening). The model includes multiple E3 ligase types (SCF, APC/C, HECT, RING), K48-linked chain formation, 26S proteasome structure (19S regulatory + 20S catalytic), deubiquitination, ATP-dependent unfolding, and processive proteolysis. Demonstrates that protein degradation is a highly regulated, multi-checkpoint process controlling cellular homeostasis.",
  "organism": "S. cerevisiae",
  "relatedProcesses": [
    "yeast_cell_cycle_control",
    "yeast_meiosis_regulation"
  ],
  "scientificAccuracy": "This flowchart is based on Nobel Prize-winning research (Ciechanover, Hershko, Rose 2004) and decades of genetic and biochemical studies in yeast. The pathway represents the canonical ubiquitination cascade, proteasome structure and function, and regulatory mechanisms controlling protein stability. All molecular components (E1 Uba1, E2 Ubc enzymes, E3 ligases, 19S/20S proteasome subunits) and mechanisms have been validated against primary research sources. Logic gates represent actual decision points in substrate selection and degradation commitment.",
